  "worklog": "# brainTrade Work Log\n*Check this anytime to see what I'm doing and how I'm thinking.*\n\n---\n\n## 2026-04-22 06:14 UTC \u2014 [P2: Smart Entry] Overnight Breaks Need a Durability Gate, Not Just Detection\n\n**Task:** Compare the late-05h break regimes against the opening behavior of 06h to decide whether overnight break detection alone is enough to matter.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive and PM remains correctly out of active hours.\n- **05h** now contains three regimes:\n  - `(0.505, 0.495)` \u2192 **50** windows\n  - `(0.480, 0.520)` \u2192 **5** windows\n  - `(0.485, 0.515)` \u2192 **5** windows\n  - `|bias| >= 45` in **29** windows, `|bias| >= 55` in **12**\n- **06h** so far reopened with zero ambiguity:\n  - `(0.505, 0.495)` \u2192 **14/14** windows\n  - `|bias| >= 45` in **4** windows, `|bias| >= 55` in **2**\n- So the late-05h break existed, but it did **not** survive the next boundary. The market returned immediately to the old carry state.\n- Wrote new research artifact: `/home/ubuntu/clawd/patches/v7l-break-durability-gate.spec.md`\n\n**My thinking:**\nBreak detection was a good first step, but it is not enough. Some breaks are just failed transitions. The strategic question is whether a new regime has enough durability to matter after it appears. If it cannot hold through the next cluster or next hour boundary, it belongs in the \"interesting but non-actionable\" bucket.\n\n**Decision:**\n- Add a **durability gate** to overnight break analysis.\n- Classify the late-05h break as **non-durable** because 06h reopened directly in the old `0.505 / 0.495` carry.\n- Keep using state transitions for research, but rank them by whether they persist.\n\n**Next:** On the next P2 heartbeat, review all observed overnight breaks and classify each as durable vs non-durable to see whether any excluded hour ever produces a break worth promoting.\n\n---\n## 2026-04-22 05:45 UTC \u2014 [P1: Copy Intelligence] PM Copy Flow Missed Both the 05h Carry Break